JIRA is supposed to be a tracking tool that is most often used as the authoritative data store of record when it comes to external audit of any sort. However, one of the first tenants of a good audit trail is that editing of the audit trail should NEVER be allowed. Fields relied on for audit purposes should only be APPEND-ONLY or else they are of questionable value for audit.

Looking at {{com.atlassian.jira.web.action.admin.user.AddUser#doExecute}} there is this piece of code:
{code:java}
if (sendEmail)
{
  userService.createUserWithNotification(result);
}
else
{
  userService.createUserNoNotification(result);
}
{code}

{{sendMail}} is a boolean value set to true only is user management is not enabled. But the problem is that the method with or without notification really mean with or without firing the {{user created}} event.

The sending of the mail is done in a listener which also does the check for external user management. So doing it in the {{AddUser}} action is doubly wrong:
* it's done in the mail listener,
* and it prevent anyone else from listening on user creation if external user management is configured.

